$CATEGORY: CIT/M4/week-10/10-5-designing-human-in-the-loop-checkpoints-when-to-require-sign

::q1:: When deciding whether a specific AI decision point requires human sign-off or can be left to autonomous action, which three factors does the framework ask you to examine? {
~Whether the AI system was built by a reputable vendor, the size of the dataset it was trained on, and whether a compliance team has previously reviewed and approved the model's outputs#No — vendor reputation and dataset size are not part of the checkpoint decision procedure; they do not tell you whether a human is needed at this specific decision.
~The speed of the AI system, the number of people affected by each decision, and whether the decision has been flagged before by an earlier review cycle or audit process#No — throughput and prior flags are operational concerns, not the structural factors that determine which oversight mode is appropriate.
=The cost of the decision being wrong, whether a human reviewer can genuinely verify the AI's output, and whether a named, empowered person is accountable if it fails#Correct — these map directly to Q1 (cost), Q2 (verifiability), and Q3 (accountability), the three questions that drive the checkpoint decision.
~Whether the AI operates in real time, whether it is connected to external databases, and whether its outputs are automatically logged and retained for a defined retention period#No — real-time operation and logging are implementation details; they do not determine which oversight mode a checkpoint requires.
#### Tests LO1 — identifying the three factors (Q1, Q2, Q3) that determine checkpoint type. Corpus §6, decision procedure table.
}

::q2:: An AI system scores job applications and passes borderline cases to a recruiter for review. The cost of an error is assessed as medium, the recruiter genuinely can evaluate the shortlist, and a named HR lead is accountable for outcomes. Applying the Judgment Framework decision table, which checkpoint type is correct? {
=Human-on-the-loop with explicit escalation triggers defined for borderline edge cases#Correct — Q1=Medium, Q2=Yes, Q3=Named maps to HOTL with escalation triggers in the decision table.
~Human-in-the-loop requiring explicit sign-off on every shortlisted candidate before invitations go out#No — mandatory pre-action sign-off (HITL) is reserved for Q1=High. A medium-cost decision with a verifiable, accountable reviewer qualifies for HOTL, not HITL.
~Human-out-of-the-loop with periodic audits of batch decisions#No — HOOTL is appropriate only for low-cost, highly reversible decisions; a medium-cost outcome with real impact on job applicants requires active monitoring, not after-the-fact audit.
~Human-in-the-loop, but only after the verification gap is fixed#No — a Q2=No gap is what triggers the "fix verification first" path. Here Q2=Yes (the recruiter can verify), so no gap exists; the path goes directly to HOTL.
#### Tests LO2 — applying the Q1/Q2/Q3 decision table to a scenario and reading off the correct checkpoint type. Corpus §6, result table row "Medium / Yes / Named."
}

::q3:: A fraud-detection system automatically blocks suspicious transactions. No human watches the individual blocks as they happen; instead, a risk analyst reads a summary report each morning and reviews exception cases once a week. Which oversight mode does this describe, and what is the appropriate constraint on using it? {
~Human-in-the-loop — the analyst's morning report review counts as a form of sign-off that retroactively authorises each block that has already taken effect#No — HITL requires approval before an action takes effect. Reading a summary report after blocks have already been applied is not pre-action sign-off.
~Human-on-the-loop — the analyst is monitoring the decision stream in real time and retains the authority to intervene at any point before a block finalises#No — HOTL requires a human who is actively watching the decision stream and can intervene immediately. A once-daily report does not provide real-time monitoring authority.
~Human-on-the-loop — the weekly exception review session qualifies as a defined escalation trigger that promotes flagged cases to higher oversight#No — an escalation trigger is a defined condition that auto-elevates a decision before or during execution, not a retrospective review cadence.
=Human-out-of-the-loop — appropriate only for low-stakes, reversible decisions where acceptable error has been explicitly set and is routinely measured#Correct — HOOTL means the AI acts fully autonomously and humans review only after the fact; it is only appropriate when the cost of error is low and the error rate is actively monitored against a defined threshold.
#### Tests LO3 — distinguishing the three oversight modes (HITL / HOTL / HOOTL) and matching HOOTL to its appropriate use case and constraint. Corpus §5, "Human-out-of-the-loop."
}

::q4:: A document-processing system routes documents scoring below 70% confidence to human review and auto-processes those scoring 70% and above. Over six months the auto-processed proportion quietly grows from 80% to 94%. Why does the framework flag this pattern as a checkpoint design failure? {
~The confidence threshold of 70% is too low — raising it to 90% or above would prevent this kind of silent drift and keep the human review queue calibrated at a size that reflects genuine uncertainty in the system's predictions#No — raising the threshold would reduce the human queue even further, compounding the problem. The issue is not that the threshold is too permissive; it is that confidence scores do not reliably track actual accuracy.
=A high confidence score is not the same as high accuracy — the system can be systematically wrong, especially for underrepresented subgroups, while still reporting high confidence, so routing by confidence alone creates a false sense of safety#Correct — the documented pitfall of confidence routing is that confidence score diverges from actual accuracy, particularly for groups underrepresented in training data. The shrinking review queue looks like improved performance but may mask expanding errors.
~The human review queue proportion of 20% is already too large and costly; the framework recommends that well-designed systems target 5% or fewer cases for human review so that reviewer attention is not diluted by volume#No — the proportion of cases requiring human review should be driven by decision risk and error rate, not by a target ratio. Reducing the queue to hit a percentage is the exact dynamic that causes silent drift.
~Confidence routing is fundamentally unsuitable for document processing workflows and the entire pattern should be replaced with deterministic rule-based filtering, which does not suffer from the same drift dynamic as probabilistic thresholds#No — confidence routing is a legitimate starting-point design pattern. The problem is relying on it as the sole escalation mechanism without auditing confidence scores against actual subgroup error rates.
#### Tests LO4 — evaluating the confidence-routing failure mode. Corpus §5 "Confidence routing" and §7 "Confidence routing pitfalls."
}

::q5:: A team is building a checkpoint matrix for a multi-component AI loan-approval pipeline. They have listed every decision-making component as a row. Which set of columns makes the matrix complete enough to be auditable? {
~Model name, training data source, and last-retraining date for each component, so reviewers can track how the underlying models have changed over the lifetime of the pipeline#No — these are model provenance details, not oversight-design decisions. They do not reveal whether the checkpoint is HITL, HOTL, or HOOTL, or what would trigger escalation.
~Decision description, expected throughput per hour, and SLA response time for human reviewers, so the operations team can staff the review queue and meet latency commitments#No — throughput and SLA are operational metrics; they do not record the Judgment Framework rationale or the conditions under which the oversight mode escalates.
=Oversight mode (HITL / HOTL / HOOTL), the Judgment Framework answers (Q1 / Q2 / Q3) that justify that mode, and the escalation triggers that apply#Correct — the checkpoint matrix needs the oversight mode choice, the documented rationale from the Judgment Framework, and the explicit conditions that would escalate a decision to higher oversight. These three make the design auditable and improvable.
~Oversight mode and a free-text notes field where the team records their reasoning in their own words, so future reviewers can understand the intent behind each checkpoint choice that was made#No — a free-text notes field is not structured enough to be auditable. The Judgment Framework answers must be recorded as distinct fields so a regulator or auditor can systematically verify the rationale and check for Q2=No or Q3=diffuse gaps.
#### Tests LO5 — designing a checkpoint matrix and identifying the required columns. Corpus §5 "Checkpoint matrix" and §6 implementation steps.
}

::q6:: Looking back at the college admissions case study (10.1) through the checkpoint design lens: admissions officers could formally override the AI score before any offer letter was sent. Yet the framework classifies this arrangement as a checkpoint design failure. Which analysis is correct? {
=The checkpoint was structurally HITL — sign-off was required before action — but functionally HOOTL, because officers received only a score with no access to the model's reasoning, making Q2 effectively unanswered and genuine verification impossible#Correct — when a human cannot actually evaluate what they are signing off on, a HITL checkpoint produces override as theater: the form of oversight without its substance. The checkpoint matrix would have exposed this Q2=No gap before deployment.
~The checkpoint failed because no escalation trigger was defined for borderline cases — specifically, adding a rule that any AI score falling within five points of the admission cutoff must automatically be routed to a senior reviewer would have fixed the underlying design flaw#No — an escalation trigger addresses when to promote a lower mode to a higher one. The admissions failure was not about missing escalation; it was that the HITL checkpoint itself was non-functional because the human had no basis for genuine verification.
~The checkpoint failed because the oversight mode was incorrectly set to HOTL when it should have been HITL — admissions officers were positioned as passive monitors of the score rather than decision-makers who actively signed off on individual admission outcomes#No — officers were required to sign off before offers went out, which is the HITL structure. The failure was not the wrong mode label but the fact that the conditions required for HITL to be genuine (Q2=Yes) were absent.
~The checkpoint was correctly designed at the structural level but failed purely in execution — officers had the information they needed but chose not to override the AI even when they privately disagreed, which is an automation complacency problem, not a design deficiency#No — while automation complacency is real, the corpus identifies the root cause here as a design gap: officers had no access to the model's reasoning, so they had no informed basis for disagreement. That is a Q2=No design defect, not a behavioral one.
#### Tests Bonus LO — re-analysing a case study through the checkpoint design lens (Q2 gap = HITL as theater). Corpus §7 "College admissions (10.1)" and §6 Q2 step.
}
